dspace-development.title: Update the oaworkflow-dev and oaworkflow X.509 certificates

comments.body:
OIT has provided a replacement PKCS12 certificate bundle, and this does import successfully as needed.

Unfortunately, there is now a separate issue when I attempt to bind this to the IIS site:

https://phaq.phunsites.net/2010/12/09/binding-ssl-in-iss-causes-a-specified-logon-session-does-not-exist-it-may-already-have-been-terminated-error/

When enquiring about the OpenSSL versions used between our environments, I found that I was using a much later version:

OIT's build version:
```
% openssl version

LibreSSL 2.8.3
```

My build version:
```
$ openssl version
OpenSSL 3.0.0 7 sep 2021 (Library: OpenSSL 3.0.0 7 sep 2021)
```

Using a Vagrant environment, I am now able to work directly with the same build of OpenSSL:

```bash
vagrant@vagrant-ubuntu-trusty-64:~/libressl-2.8.3$ /usr/local/libressl/bin/openssl version
LibreSSL 2.8.3
```

After trying to further diagnose this from within the Windows Server environment, I have found the following:

![image.png](https://images.zenhubusercontent.com/5b5b6aed981c3204c9ed06c8/b6f0995a-bf9f-4f62-9f94-045eeed2a98b)

It appears that the key is not stored in the PKCS12 exports.

comments.body: Example WMTSCapabilities.xml: https://gist.github.com/eliotjordan/da5a1c4ad1a1b8b2b7bd490d3929a53d

websequencediagrams.com: 

![mosaic-json-request.png](https://images.zenhubusercontent.com/5cba1f45fec3b63424e0f761/b7f3b616-25d8-4013-83bc-d816e5dd9db7)

```
title mosaic.json  Request


actor User
User -> +cloudfront-viewer-request: Puts map-tiles link in GIS software
note right of cloudfront-viewer-request: is a lambda
cloudfront-viewer-request -> +figgy: get s3 url of mosaic.json (including fingerprint)
note right of cloudfront-viewer-request: optional cache here.
note right of cloudfront-viewer-request: optional fallback here to fingerprint-less mosaic.json
note right of figgy: calculate fingerprint
note right of figgy: check s3 for fingerprinted json file
note right of figgy: generate it to s3 if needed, both with and without fingerprint
figgy --> -cloudfront-viewer-request: return s3 url


note right of cloudfront-viewer-request: put s3 url as a param
cloudfront-viewer-request -> +titiler lambda: request the image tile
titiler lambda --> -cloudfront-viewer-request: return the image tile

cloudfront-viewer-request --> -User: return image tiles
```
Figgy should store the mosaic.json files on s3 under a bucket path named after the figgy resource id.

comments.body:
Assets are being loaded from `app/assets` directly on staging, hence the appearance that everything looks normal there; staging needs an environment config, and the image assets loading from the CSS need to be referenced by `asset_url`.  

Not sure how to add a test to determine whether images in CSS are rendering or not.

As of 14 Dec, we are able to do a *partial* authentication to shibboleth. However, it is returning the user to the wrong url. After troubleshooting with @kayiwa and Jay at OIT, here is the diagnosis:

```
using this URL https://vireo-staging.princeton.edu/Shibboleth.sso/Login
I was able to see the application hit our IDP

Within the SAML request: the ACS URL is: https://vireo-staging/Shibboleth.sso/SAML2/POST

To fix this, you need to update your application to use the correct ACS URL of https://vireo-staging.princeton.edu/Shibboleth.sso/SAML2/POST which is within your metadata file.

Thanks, Jay
```

That metadata file is being generated by `mod_shib`, our shibboleth plugin for apache2. I have been trying to figure out how to get it to alter what it creates. I may need to create it the first time manually, and then hand-edit the file and put it into ansible. I'm going to try that next.
At this point we assume this is obsolete. Re-open with more detail if it's still needed.
